  "title": "The Societies of Honor",
  "story": [
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "326c1dfb2a267be8",
      "text": "For Graeber, the next ... stage of the transformation of human economies into commercial economies is reached when, through habituation to and beyond human trafficking, not only are members of one's own society forcibly degraded to the status of an object of value and sold to stranges or to foreign countries, but an objectifying liberation of \"intrinsically\" unique, irreplaceable, and therefore incommensurable persons becomes the internal social rule, when, in other words, the violent practice of slavery entails a kind of internal moral perversion. The societies of honor, as Graeber calls them, are the ones in which the cult of (male) honor on the one hand still reminds us of the original and actual dignity of man, but on the other hand has already become a form of accumulative capital."
    },
